					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">I think C is great for NES development. Yes, you may have performance issues, but these things have solutions. You can monitor your program's performance as you go, and you can write additional assembly code where performance becomes critical. Otherwise, I find the productivity increase writing C code versus assembly is immense.<br /><br />Last year I made a music program for NES, mostly in C except for a minimal assembly layer for interacting with the NES: <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=i5vyQO81qNc" class="postlink">http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=i5vyQO81qNc</a><br />I released the source, feel free to use it as an example, if you need one: <a href="http://rainwarrior.ca/music/coltrane_src.zip" class="postlink">http://rainwarrior.ca/music/coltrane_src.zip</a></div>

